I‚Äôd violate my apolitical credo to comment on any reasoning I might impute to the practices of the Catholic‚Äîor any other‚Äîchurch. I merely wanted to express my aesthetic appreciation of its rites, because they are beautiful. 

As for Urban I. Yes, there are plenty of myths swirling about him, but his instituting the use of silver vessels for liturgy is somewhat likely not to be one, which is why I‚Äôd picked it as an interesting tidbit. It comes from Liber Pontificalis, whose entries for the early popes primarily list two kinds of details: (a) Administrative or liturgical innovations (constituit ut‚Ä¶) and (b) relics, martyrs, miracles, etc. The latter are usually anachronistic and thus easily disproved. The former, though‚Äîwell, it depends. On the one hand L.P. is the first source to mention Urban I‚Äôs silver decree and this 2 centuries post facto, while contemporarily writing Hippolytus doesn‚Äôt mention it. On the other hand, the claim is chronologically credible and no other source contradicts it. So we‚Äôve got something which is attested and, while not verifiable, is not falsifiable. It is also  historically plausible, with economic, political, and material context that fits neatly. Many such administrative ‚Äúconstituit‚Äù items may be retrojections, assigning later customs to early popes to lend them apostolic authority, but this one smells like the real thing (not the least because it is such a short, dry little note in the L.P. As myths go, it‚Äôd make a really boring one).

